              "version": "1"
            },
            "response_id": "resp_0f45ed8c7f18805e0069a88a75cd908194a214d9e08c1747a4",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Kubernetes (often shortened to **K8s**) grew out of Google’s experience running large-scale production workloads in containers.\n\n- **Origins at Google (pre-2014):** Kubernetes was inspired by Google’s internal cluster management systems—especially **Borg** (and lessons from its successor, **Omega**)—which automated scheduling, scaling, and recovery of services across huge fleets of machines. These ideas were adapted into an open, general-purpose container orchestrator.  \n\n- **Open-sourced by Google (2014):** Google **announced and open-sourced Kubernetes in 2014**, positioning it as a platform to deploy and manage containerized applications. The name comes from the Greek for “helmsman” or “pilot,” reflecting its role in “steering” containers.  \n\n- **Community governance via CNCF (2015):** To ensure vendor-neutral stewardship and encourage broad industry adoption, Google **donated Kubernetes to the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)** in 2015, helping turn it into a central open-source project in the cloud-native ecosystem.  \n\n- **Maturation and widespread adoption (2016–present):** Kubernetes rapidly became the de facto standard for container orchestration, with major cloud providers and vendors building managed Kubernetes services and a large ecosystem of add-ons (networking, observability, service mesh, GitOps, etc.). Its governance and development continue in the open under the CNCF.  \n\nIf you want, I can also give a brief timeline of key milestone releases/features (e.g., deployments/replicasets, CRDs/operators, etc.).",
                "annotations": [],
                "logprobs": []
              }
            ],
            "status": "completed"
